A vegetarian pantry that is stocked with the basics should contain:

Grain products: rice (especially brown, arborio, jasmine, basmati and sweet), millet, couscous, quinoa, kasha, wild rice (aquatic grass), buckwheat, barley, polenta, and whole grain flours. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/c\/cd\/Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet1.jpg\/v4-460px-Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/c\/cd\/Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet1.jpg\/v4-760px-Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Pasta and noodles: pasta made from grain products (e.g., wheat pasta, rice pasta), noodles (e.g., udon, buckwheat etc.). Try to avoid quick-cook noodles; these tend to have a lot of the healthy nutrients removed and are often high in trans-fats. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/0\/02\/Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet2.jpg\/v4-460px-Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/0\/02\/Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet2.jpg\/v4-760px-Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Legumes: dried legumes (peas, split peas, lentils, puy lentils, chickpeas/garbanzo, kidney beans, pinto beans etc. ), tins/cans of legumes, shelf-stored tofu. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/9\/96\/Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet3.jpg\/v4-460px-Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/9\/96\/Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet3.jpg\/v4-760px-Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Instant mixes for veggie burgers, falafels, etc. Try to prefer organic options and low sodium. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/e\/eb\/Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet4.jpg\/v4-460px-Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/e\/eb\/Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet4.jpg\/v4-760px-Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Vegetables and fruits: There are various ways of storing these in the pantry:{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/26\/Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet5.jpg\/v4-460px-Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/26\/Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet5.jpg\/v4-760px-Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Tins/cans of fruit in natural syrup, tins/cans of some vegetables. Try to avoid sourcing a lot of your fruit and veggies in this way because canned varieties lose nutrients, have high sodium, and can leach chemicals from the can soldering/composition into the food over time. Always choose cans that are free from dents, and be sure to check use-by dates. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/ab\/Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet6.jpg\/v4-460px-Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet6.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/ab\/Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet6.jpg\/v4-760px-Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet6.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Preserved fruit and vegetables. Follow the instructions carefully if you make your own at home. Dehydrated fruits and veggies can also be kept in the pantry for reconstitution. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/d\/dc\/Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet8.jpg\/v4-460px-Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet8.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/d\/dc\/Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet8.jpg\/v4-760px-Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet8.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Dried fruit. A must for both eating and cooking with. Apricots, peaches, pears, apple, nectarines etc. are all great choices. Beware of added sugar; dried pineapple, strawberries, paw-paw, kiwifruit etc. often have considerable added sugar. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/e\/e4\/Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet9.jpg\/v4-460px-Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet9.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/e\/e4\/Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet9.jpg\/v4-760px-Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet9.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Nuts and seeds: Nuts and seeds should be eaten quickly to ensure that they remain fresh. Only purchase small amounts at a time. It is handy to always have on hand walnuts, almonds, sunflower seeds, pumpkin seeds, cashews, pecans and sesame seeds. Peanuts are a personal choice given modern allergy problems. Nut and seed butters are also very useful to keep on hand; consider tahini, peanut butter, cashew nut butter, almond butter etc. Some require refrigeration on opening. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/63\/Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet10.jpg\/v4-460px-Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet10.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/63\/Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet10.jpg\/v4-760px-Stock-a-Vegetarian-Pantry-Step-3Bullet10.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


